<TEXT>
the reagan administration says it is looking 
at ways to help thousands of nicaraguan rebels facing acute food 
shortages during stalled negotiations between the contras and the 
sandinista government 
state department spokesman charles redman said friday the 
alternatives include direct deliveries of food to rebel forces or 
cash payments to be used for food purchases 
any such move would almost certainly touch off a vigorous 
sandinista protest that the terms of the temporary ceasefire 
agreed to by the contras and the government on march 23 was being 
violated 
the nicaraguan government maintains that us humanitarian aid 
can be delivered only after the rebels have been resettled in seven 
designated ceasefire zones and if a verification commission 
confirms the contents 
no contras have been resettled because there has been no 
agreement on ground rules governing activities in the ceasefire 
zones both the administration and the contras have accused the 
sandinistas of resorting to delaying tactics to deny the rebels 
access to food 
although redman provided no specifics the aid whether food or 
cash apparently would be sent into nicaragua by rebel forces 
based in contra camps in honduras near the nicaraguan border 
the aid program is being managed by the us agency for 
international development which began deliveries to honduranbased 
contras two weeks ago 
aid has denied charges by nicaraguan president daniel ortega 
that the deliveries contained weapons and are illegal because there 
was no prior inspection by an officially designated verification 
commission 
the 48 million aid package approved by congress five weeks 
ago includes 10 million for the commission which includes 
nicaraguan cardinal miguel obando y bravo and organization of 
american states secretary general joao baena soares 
redman said the administration has reached tentative agreement 
on funds for the commission but no plan has been received from the 
oas that meets minimum accountability standards 
</TEXT>
