<TEXT>
the reagan administration is expressing 
skepticism about frances claim that no reward was given to iran 
for its help in the freeing of three french hostages from lebanon 
state department spokesman charles redman said that providing 
rewards to hostage takers could prolong the ordeal of the remaining 
18 hostages in lebanon nine of those hostages are americans 
redman also called on iran on friday to use its influence 
newly demonstrated this week over kidnappers in lebanon to help 
secure the release of the 18 captives 
both the french and iranian governments acknowledged the iranian 
role in the releases of the three french hostages jeanpaul 
kauffmann marcel carton and marcel fontaine 
once again this demonstrates the substantial influence iran 
holds over terrorist kidnappers redman said adding that it is 
not yet clear what prompted iran to take the action it did 
in any case he said we again call on iran to exercise its 
proven influence immediately to secure the release of the other 
hostages still held in lebanon 
france has denied that any money was paid for the hostages 
freedom but prime minister jacques chirac has made vague 
references to a bargain with iran 
expressing doubts about the propriety of french actions redman 
said weve noted the french statements on the subject we will 
closely monitor future developments and we will be especially 
sensitive to any actions which could be seen as rewarding the 
taking of hostages 
redman reaffirmed the longstanding us view that the taking of 
hostages should not be rewarded 
such behavior serves only to encourage more terrorism and 
prolong the ordeal of other hostages including the nine innocent 
americans 
redman also disputed the contention of peggy say sister of us 
hostage terry anderson who said it almost appears that france 
placed a higher priority on the lives of the french hostages than 
the american government does on the lives of us hostages 
i would reject the notion that our government is less 
concerned than any other government redman said 
anderson 40 is the chief middle east correspondent of the 
associated press he was abducted on march 16 1985 and has been 
held longer than any other hostage in lebanon 
redman said president reagan reflected feelings of the entire 
administration when he said that he shared the frustration of the 
hostages families 
they too are the victims of terrorism he said we are 
deeply concerned about the hostages and are doing what we can to 
obtain their release 
