<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency has given 
a qualified endorsement to a planned sale of offshore oil and gas 
leases in the north atlantic despite a top agency officials belief 
that the 1989 sale should be scuttled 
michael r deland the epas regional administrator for new 
england said in a memo released friday by a leasing opponent that 
the plan is environmentally unacceptable and that epa should 
urge the interior department to cancel or defer it 
but epa superiors in washington overruled deland and sent the 
interior department a qualified endorsement of the planned february 
sale for exploration only of 55 million acres off the 
northeast coast from maine to new jersey 
deland wrote in the may 3 memo we find that the proposed 
lease sale 96 is environmentally unacceptable because it places at 
unnecessary risk a proven renewable fishery resource of national 
and global biological and commercial value 
deland echoed many of the same arguments stressed by 
environmentalists and local new england officials who oppose 
drilling on georges bank a major fishing area off the new england 
coast 
he said the risks of a major oil spill or blowout from 
exploration and production activities are much greater than 
interior department officials have stated 
the regional chief also noted the importance of georges banks 
180 millionayear fishing industry that accounts for about 
onefifth of the dollar value of all fish caught in the united 
states 
congress has placed a leasing ban on the most fragile areas of 
georges bank but deland warned that many highly sensitive areas 
remain available for lease and thus exposed to the risks associated 
with offshore oil and gas exploration and production 
deland also quoted government estimates which say there is an 86 
percent chance that no oil or gas would be found a figure repeated 
by environmentalists and illustrated by the limited industry 
interest in the area in past years 
rep gerry e studds dmass author of the congressional 
moratorium released the memo friday he said he hopes to use 
delands comments to convince congress to expand the current 
leasing ban to all of georges bank a move he proposed for the 
first time last week 
richard e sanderson director of epas office of federal 
activities who sent the agencys final recommendation to interior 
officials this week said the current lease plan poses almost no 
environmental risk and he pointed to new englands growing 
energy needs 
i just couldnt find a rationale to agree with him deland 
based on the mathematical evaluations sanderson said in a 
telephone interview the best technical data said there was 
minimal to zero risk for exploration 
sanderson added that the revised sale proposal is limited to 
leases for exploration only more risky fullscale production 
which the agency has concerns about would require another level of 
bureaucratic approval he said 
studds a leading opponent of georges bank drilling said the 
most knowledgeable senior official has been overruled by the 
ideologues 
