<TEXT>
four out of five married women in beijing want 
two or more children despite the government policy limiting each 
couple to only one child according to a survey released today 
the official xinhua news agency said a survey of 7539 married 
women in the beijing area found that twothirds wanted two children 
and 138 percent wanted three or more it said just 199 percent 
were satisfied with one child 
the survey was conducted by the beijing statistics bureau 
of those women who already have a child 585 percent surveyed 
said they had agreed to respect the one coupleone child policy 
while 244 percent have not decided and 121 percent do not want to 
comply 
china adopted its onechild policy at the beginning of the 1980s 
in an attempt to limit its population now at 107 billion to 12 
billion by the year 2000 
the policy has been generally successful in urban areas where 
there are housing shortages and most women have jobs 
but the onechild concept has made little headway in the more 
conservative countryside where couples want boys to take care of 
them in their old age and children to help out on the farm 
many rural couples enriched by economic reforms that have 
brought back family farming have little difficulty in paying off 
fines imposed for having more than one child 
population experts now say relaxed attitudes toward family 
planning and the fact that couples from the babyboom generation of 
the 1960s are now starting their own families have pushed 
population growth beyond acceptable levels and made the target for 
the year 2000 impossible to achieve 
</TEXT>
