the tailors of savile row britains worldfamous 
custom tailoring district took to the street with their needles 
thread and scissors saturday for a fitting centennial celebration 
to kick off events marking the federation of merchant tailors 
100th anniversary a team of 20 cutters tailors and finishers 
assembled a gray striped woolen suit in just nine hours 
the cornerstone of a gentlemans wardrobe normally would take 
eight weeks to complete require one or two fittings and cost 
1400 to 2250 said federation president robert bright 
im taking the opportunity of the centenary to remove the 
metaphoric frosted windows and curtained windows that were a 
feature of tailor shops for far too long said bright also 
chairman of the 159yearold wells of mayfair firm 
savile row a short narrow street in central london was sealed 
off to traffic and tents were erected where passersby could watch 
the 90 separate steps involved in fashioning a threepiece suit 
the marathon pinning basting and sewing session began at 9 am 
with the cutting of the fabric and the last button was in place by 
612 pm 
martyn lewis a british broadcasting corp tv anchorman with a 
34inch waist and 41inch chest was the guinea pig he requested 
only that the garment be made for sitting down in so he could 
read the news without any inelegant wrinkling of the lapel of his 
bespoke suit a term derived from customers bespeaking 
their individual requirements 
