<TEXT>
a rare exhibition of american impressionist 
painter childe hassams flag pictures explodes into view sunday at 
the national gallery of art with all the brilliant optimism of a 
fourth of july fireworks display 
it is the first time since 1922 before the artists death that 
his patriotic canvases from world war i have been drawn from widely 
scattered public museums and private collections and shown 
together the lenders include ibm frank sinatra and the white 
house 
hassam the most important american impressionist at the turn of 
the century was enthralled by the majesty and symbolic power of 
the us and allied flags banners and bunting that festooned new 
york city streets mostly along fifth avenue for wartime parades 
and fundraising rallies 
his 31 flag pictures painted from 1916 until the war ended in 
1919 are preeminent examples of how art could serve 
patriotism says ilene susan fort associate curator of american 
art at the los angeles county museum of art which organized the 
exhibition 
hassams flags frequently are framed by manhattan churches and 
skyscrapers as symbols of the moral force of the allied cause and 
americas emergence as a world power she said 
the national gallery exhibition includes 23 of the flag 
paintings which were sold individually after 1922 after failure of 
a plan to purchase a group of them as a war memorial for new york 
city 
ms fort said five of the flag paintings sold in the 1920s 
including three depicting women watching parades from flagdraped 
windows have since vanished and their whereabouts if they still 
exist are unknown she said she hoped that word of the exhibition 
might encourage the owners to step forward 
when the show closes at the national gallery on july 18 it will 
travel to the los angeles museum aug 21 through oct 30 the amon 
carter museum at fort worth texas jan 7 through march 12 and 
the new york historical society april 20 through june 25 
the national gallery show is the second in a threepart series 
devoted to american impressionist artists and underwritten by bell 
atlantic the first was an exhibition of paintings by william 
merritt chase last year the series will end in the fall of 1989 
with the works of john twachtman 
</TEXT>
