<TEXT>
the inflight breakup of a 19yearold aloha 
airlines boeing 737 has heightened concern about the safety of 
older jetliners but the problem has been known for years 
nearly a decade ago the industry and its regulators agreed to 
develop new safeguards against potentially catastrophic cracks and 
corrosion with a large portion of the nations commercial fleet 
already approaching old age a program begun in 1983 covers nearly 
1000 planes now flying 
but some aviation safety experts remained worried that while the 
monitoring program looked good on paper it might not always be 
carried through and that federal regulators werent able to 
backstop all cases 
according to the national transportation safety board the 
agency has investigated more than 80 incidents and accidents 
involving aircraft fatigue cracks or corrosion since 1975 though 
many were isolated to landing gear or engine problems at least 15 
cases involved cracks or corrosion on an aircrafts outer skin or 
on control devices 
on april 28 a 20foot section of the upper cabin of an aloha 
boeing 737 ripped away at 24000 feet exposing passengers to the 
open air and sweeping a flight attendant to her death before the 
pilot managed an emergency landing 
since then the federal aviation administration has ordered 
renewed inspections of older boeing 737s including mandatory 
highfrequency electronic testing of those that have more than 
50000 landings but safety experts note that special visual 
inspections of those planes including the aloha craft already 
were required at the time of the accident 
the cause of the aloha accident is yet to be determined 
precisely but the episode demonstrates a need to reevaluate the 
issues surrounding the aging fleet question especially as it 
relates to fatigue and corrosion cracking suggests joseph nall 
the ntsb member who headed the initial investigation at aloha last 
week 
investigators are certain the accident stemmed from a structural 
failure the unanswered question is why did such a structural 
problem on the 19yearold airplane which had nearly 90000 
landings go undetected 
where did the system of warnings inspections and preventative 
maintenance go awry 
its one thing to issue a piece of paper its something else 
to know with confidence that this stuff is being done the way you 
know it can be done says co miller a veteran aviation safety 
consultant and former government investigator it isnt just a 
simple issue of putting out an faa directive or a service 
bulletin 
aloha officials have maintained all along that they complied 
with all faa directives in connection with the plane 
according to the faa there are about 1000 commercial jets 
boeing 727s 737s 747s mcdonnell douglas dc9s and dc8s that 
are subject to the program designed in 1983 to monitor older 
aircraft more closely for structural defects 
the only reason there is the focus on the 737 is because it 
had the accident declares ben cosgrove vice president for 
engineering at the boeing airplane co 
the program was established after the airlines made it clear 
they plan to keep their jets longer because declining fuel costs 
lessened the attraction for investing in new more fuelefficient 
planes whatever new jets are bought are usually flown to expand 
service rather than as replacements 
as a result since 1979 the average age of the aircraft fleet 
belonging to the major airlines has increased from 1028 years to 
1253 years according to avmark inc an arlington va aircraft 
consulting and appraisal firm 
there are probably about 2300 airplanes now in service that 
are fundamentally over 20 years old built before 1968 says 
boeings cosgrove while these planes are capable of flying years 
longer after the 20year mark you should start expecting to see 
some more damage occur through fatigue and corrosion he 
acknowledges 
but both boeing and competitor mcdonnell douglas maintain that 
with close inspections and prompt maintenance these jetliners 
should have no problem flying well beyond their design life 
mcdonnell douglas a few years ago tested an old dc9 to an 
equivalent of 208000 landing cycles to see how it would hold up 
as a result of the test were very confident we have a dc9 life 
of at least 104000 landing cycles says jj mcgrew the 
manufacturers director of aircraft design 
different parts of the plane are affected differently but the 
strength of its fuselage and outer skin is most affected by the 
number of takeoff and landings each time a plane is pressurized 
the cabin wall expands slightly and then when depressurized it 
retracts that cycle can take its toll and can lead to a 
potentially dangerous failure if critical parts such as metal 
joints are weakened by corrosion according to technical experts 
the aloha aircraft had nearly 90000 such cycles in only 33000 
hours of flying since most flights shuttled among the hawaiian 
islands 
ironically it is such shorthaul flights that often are served 
by the older jets perhaps the most heavily traveled shorthaul 
system is eastern airlines washingtonnew yorkboston shuttle 
where 17 older boeing 727s are in use 
each of the eastern planes falls under the special faa 
inspection and maintenance program begun for older jets five years 
ago according to roger ferguson easterns vice president for 
maintenance and engineering although none approach the number of 
landings experienced by the aloha aircraft 
while maintenance costs for the older planes are higher as 
much as 1 times more for a 20 yearold plane as a 5yearold craft 
the older boeing jets continue to perform economically ferguson 
said the planes including the top of the fuselage are visually 
inspected for cracks every 1100 landings said ferguson 
john obrien safety and engineering specialist at the air line 
pilots association says there is an inadequate number of faa 
inspectors and complains that airlines occasionally ignore 
maintenance bulletins from the manufacturers because they are not 
mandatory he says the faa often is under pressure from the 
industry not to issue mandatory directives except as a last 
resort 
