an outbreak of legionnaires disease at the 
british broadcasting corporations headquarters has increased to 19 
confirmed cases and 45 suspected cases the bbc said saturday 
fortyone people are hospitalized and nine are seriously ill a 
corporation spokeswoman said speaking on condition of anonymity in 
keeping with british practice 
doctors dealing with the outbreak said they expected more cases 
to develop in the next few days but they believed there was no 
further risk of infection in the area around the buildings 
the department of health wrote to britains district medical 
officers on friday urging them to warn doctors to be on the 
lookout for pneumonia victims who may have been near bbc 
headquarters recently 
legionnaires disease which produces symptoms similar to 
pneumonia is often caused by bacteria from watercooled air 
conditioning units the bbc said its air systems in the main 
broadcasting house and nearby duchess street building were 
disinfected last week 
the disease was first diagnosed in july 1976 after 221 people 
contracted it in philadelphia and it takes its name from the 
outbreak at the pennsylvania american legion convention there 
thirtyfour of the victims died doctors in the united states say 
legionnaires disease has been fatal in about 15 percent of cases 
