reforms nor resorting to force by the government were the answer to 
polands problems 
the statements were his strongest since the labor unrest began 
certainly strikes are a justified method to defend justice in 
the socioeconomic and sociopolitical fields and this is part 
of the churchs social doctrine the pope said 
he stressed the need for a dialogue and said here we are 
touching the heart of the problem the problem of the lack of true 
democracy that i think is the crucial problem the central problem 
of poland 
the roman catholic church which traditionally has played a 
major role in predominantly catholic poland supported solidarity 
the first free labor union in the soviet bloc when it was created 
in 1980 solidarity was suspended by the government in december 
1981 and subsequently outlawed 
john paul said he had no reason to doubt soviet leader mikhail 
gorbachevs declared intentions for reforms but said it is not 
easy to democratize a system that is by definition dictatorial and 
totalitarian 
john paul also took issue with moves in the us congress that 
would single out bolivia peru and paraguay three of the four 
countries on his itinerary for economic aid sanctions on grounds 
they are failing to cooperate with the united states in the war on 
drugs 
well are there only these countries he asked raising his 
voice are only these countries responsible and guilty or 
are there others that collaborate that profit from this and are 
not punished if not whole countries then groups 
the three countries need help not a punishment or a 
sanction he added 
a vatican official traveling with the pope who briefed reporters 
on grounds of anonymity said john paul was referring to the 
responsibility of drug consumers in the united states and other 
countries as well as international traffickers 
drug trafficking and its international implications is expected 
to be one of the popes major themes as he travels to 
cocaineproducing centers in bolivia after ending his 46hour visit 
