<TEXT>
comics impresario stan lee says the secret of 
transferring a character from comic book to television successfully 
is to avoid making the show a carbon copy 
lee transformed marvel comics into a publishing phenomenon 20 
years ago and made spiderman the fantastic four and the 
incredible hulk as popular on college campuses as lord of the 
flies a separate peace and catcher in the rye 
as editor art director and head writer he wrote at least two 
and sometimes five comic books a week for 25 years he now writes 
the spiderman newspaper comic strip 
the incredible hulk was a popular series on cbs from 1978 to 
1982 it won three emmy awards and inspired a saturday morning 
animated series that ran on nbc from 1982 to 1985 
it comes back sunday may 22 in a special movie for nbc the 
incredible hulk returns lou ferrigno and bill bixby return in 
their roles as the hulk and as david banner the hulks alter ego 
joining them are eric kramer as thor and steve levitt as dr donald 
blake 
when spiderman started in the newspapers you had 
superman and star trek and star wars said lee now 
spiderman is in 500 papers and the others are gone you have to 
realize that each medium has its own style so what i did with 
spiderman was make it more like mary worth 
the trouble when people try to bring comic book characters to 
television or the movies is that they try to do it exactly as the 
original when we brought the hulk to television we changed it 
in the comics he could talk a little on tv he doesnt talk at all 
in the comics thor is a doctor who can change into the god of 
thunder we can put a thought balloon over his head but in the 
movie hes two separate characters that way they can talk to each 
other and move the story along 
spiderman failed as a television series it was 
terrible said lee they didnt understand what spiderman was 
supposed to be i was a consultant i learned that being a 
consultant means you give your opinion but nobody listens to you 
the amazing spiderman and the incredible hulk were on 
the air in a period when television was enamored of comic booktype 
superheroes other shows included the greatest american hero 
the new adventures of wonder woman buck rogers in the 25th 
century the sixmillion dollar man and the bionic woman 
lee moved from new york to los angeles 10 years ago when marvel 
began licensing its comic characters for animated series 
i write at home he said i cant write at the office 
when i started writing all the books i asked for wednesdays off to 
stay home and write then i asked for tuesdays and thursdays it 
finally ended up with me going to the office two days a week and 
writing at home the rest of the week here i take off wednesdays 
to stay home and write the spiderman newspaper strip 
asked why the hulk is popular lee said no matter how 
powerful we are or how competent we are we always wish we were 
more so there are things in life that frustrate us when banner 
becomes angry he turns into this character of raw strength and 
power he can overcome things that upset him i think we all have 
that fantasy 
when hes the hulk hes not very bright were glad to see 
someone that powerful isnt too smart 
he laughed its funny how you get all the theories after the 
fact when i created the series i was thinking of a frankensteins 
monster a good guy whos misunderstood then i thought of dr 
jekyll and mr hyde i told artist jack kirby lets make a hero 
out of a monster 
lee who joined marvel comics when he was 16 said 
superheroes arent a tough sell people love fantasies look at 
king solomons mines or robin hood the trouble is most people 
dont know how to do fantasy they either make it too silly and 
adults wont accept it or they make it too dull 
you have to walk a fine line you have to be realistic and 
believable then people will accept something fantastic the 
incredible hulk asks you to believe that a man can turn into 
another creature everything else is very real 
</TEXT>
