<TEXT>
oil prices have risen in reaction to an expected 
rise in demand and fears of a us supply squeeze caused by a major 
refinery fire 
the rise on friday was magnified by shortcovering a 
priceboosting occurrence caused by traders who repurchase borrowed 
oil they had sold earlier on the hunch that prices would fall 
on the new york mercantile exchange the june contract for west 
texas intermediate crude oil rose 35 cents per 42gallon barrel to 
close at 1774 
among refined products traded on the exchange wholesale 
unleaded gasoline rose 91 cent a gallon to 5152 cents and 
wholesale heating oil rose 85 cent a gallon to 4742 cents 
traders said predictions of a rising demand for petroleum 
caused partly by the impending summer driving season and a growing 
domestic economy was one reason for the rise in prices 
they also said an explosion at a shell oil co refinery in 
norco la which helped boost prices thursday continued to buoy 
the market friday although the facility produces a miniscule 
fraction of total consumption some traders said the explosion 
could disrupt the flow of supplies from the gulf coast 
as with most oneday price moves no trend emerged for the oil 
market which has been volatile largely because of failed efforts 
by the organization of petroleum exporting countries to restrict 
output and stabilize prices 
